Sharding

Scenario: we have 700GB of size documents having index as student, but i have two node of capacity 500GB each

1. Sharding is a way to divide indices into smaller pieces
2. Each piece is called shard
3. Sharding is done at index level
4. sharding improves performance by parallelization of queries

Example: 900Gb = students (800GB) + teacher (100GB)
                 400GB +   400GB + 100GB
		   node1     node2

-> whenever an index is created by default a shard (D) is created, D -> A,B (two shards)
-> a query comes to the node and the same query will run in both the shards parallelly/simultaneously

-> 1 Shard -> max can hold 2 billion documents
-> lets say now i want to store 10 billion documents
-> do sharding on that 1 shard, breaks into 10 shards, each can hold 2 billion documents

How to do Sharding:
-> split API
-> shrink API

#############################################################################################################################################################

REPLICATION

simply put copying of shards in case of disk failures (Fault Tolerance)

-> When a student index is created, a shard will be created 'S' (present in NodeA)
-> now due to some failure the data present in NodeA might get lost
-> so we need to replication of shard 'S' -> 'R'
-> for the same index now we have 2 shards, all these shards/replicas come under a group 'Replication Group' ('S','R')
-> 'S' -> Primary Shard, 'R' -> Replica Shard
-> All the replica shards should be assigned to other node (NodeB -> R1, R2)
-> fault tolerance & parallelization

Example:

PUT /fruits
GET /_cat/indices?v
GET /_cat/shards?v -> will see 2 shards one is primary and the other one is replica (UNASSIGNED)
GET /-cluster/health

'/' at beginning is optional

we can observe, health = yellow, pri = 1, rep = 1 (by default one replica shard will be there)
why yellow -> since the replica shard is not assigned to any other node, the current node is at risk (yellow) as if something happens the data is lost
even cluster health will become yellow (at Risk)

