#############################################################################################################################################################

ROUTING

-> On which shard does the ES store document
-> How does ES search for a document

The process of resolving a shard for a document

1. when inserting a new doc, shard_num = has(_routing) % num_primary_shards
2. default routing = hash(_id) % 2 -> this will match with any of the two primary shards and doc will be inserted in that shard
3. when searching: GET /student/_doc/_id -> the same formula will be used to identify the shard and ES search only in that shard

Problem: what if at the time of insertion of doc there were 3 primary shards and the doc got inserted in primary shard 3, then if the shards were increased to 4, then during search of the same doc that shard_num generated might be diff

Solution: in ELS you cannot increase the shard number once the document is inserted in index

#############################################################################################################################################################

How Elasticsearch Read Data:

GET /student/_doc/100 -> Coordination Node (Load Balancer) -> Data Node -> Routing -> Replication Group (P, R) -> ARS (Adaptive Replica Selection) -> R -> final document -> coordination node -> client

ARS -> selects the replica where the search is more optimized/free and not down

How Elasticsearch Write Data:

PUT student/_doc/100 (request) -> Coordination node -> Data Node -> Routing -> Replication group (PS, R)

-> request comes to replication group
1. The doc need to be stored in PS
2. Validate the request and doc
3. save to PS
4. Then save in all replica

