Mapping

1. Defines how documents and their fields are stored and indexed.
2. It essentially describes the data structure of your documents, including data types of fields, how they should be analyzed
3. While dynamic mapping can be helpful for quickly getting started with Elasticsearch and handling unknown fields, explicit mapping is essential for data control, consistency, and optimizing the search performance. It allows us to define the schema that best fits your data and ensures that Elasticsearch behaves as expected, even as your data evolves over time.

-> Preventing Type conflicts
-> Elasticsearch doesn't need to spend resources analyzing and guessing the data types of every new field
-> Explicit mappings allow you to define validation rules and ensure data integrity during indexing.


Dynamic Mapping:

PUT student/_doc/1
{
  "name": "Ajay",
  "age": 20
}

GET student/_mapping

{
  "student": {
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "age": {
          "type": "long"
        },
        "name": {
          "type": "text",
          "fields": {
            "keyword": {
              "type": "keyword",
              "ignore_above": 256
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

