Aliases:

1. In Elasticsearch, an alias is an additional name or label assigned to one or more indexes. It acts as a pointer to the underlying indexes, allowing users to interact with them using a more user friendly name. 
2. Aliases are dynamic and can be added, removed, or changed at any time without reindexing the data.

Use cases:

Abstraction and Decoupling:

Aliases provide an abstraction layer, separating the physical index names from the logical names used in applications. this decoupling is beneficial when you want to change or reorganize your index structure without affecting your applications.

Blue-Green Deployments

During the deployment of a new version of an index, aliases can be used to perform blue-green deployment. By switching the alias from the old index to the new one, you can ensure zero downtime and smooth transition.

Filtered Queries

Aliases enable the use of filtered queries. You can define an alias with a specific filter, and all queries routed through that alias will be automatically filtered accordingly.

Cross-Cluster search

Aliases can also be used to perform cross-cluster search, allowing you to run queries across multiple clusters as if they were a single entity.

