Elasticsearch Query Types

1. One of the core functionalities of Elasticsearch is the ability to perform searches on indexed data using the _search endpoint
2. The _search endpoint allows you to execute complex queries against your data and retrieve relevant results efficiently.
3. Elasticsearch provides a flexible and expressive query language called Query DSL (Domain specific language) that allows you to construct various types of queries. These queries can range from simple term matches to complex nested queries involving aggregations, filters, and more.

GET /index_name/_search
{
  "query": {
    // your query goes here
  },
  // Additional parameters and options can be included here
}

Some of the common query types

Match Query: This query is used to perform full-text search on a field. It matches documents that contain a specific term. (relevant data, not exact match)
Disjunction Max Query: Combines multiple queries and returns documents that match any of the queries with the highest score.
Multi-Match Query: A versatile query that allows you to run the same query across multiple fields and combines the results.
IDs Query: The Ids query allows you to specify an array of documents IDs to match. It retrieves documents that have Ids that match any of the provided IDs
Term Query: This query is used to find documents that contains a specific exact term in a particular field.
Range Query: It matches documents where the field value falls within a specified range of values.
Bool Query: A Boolean query that allows you to combine multiple queries using Boolean operators (must, should, must_not, filter) to create complex queries.
Exists Query: This query matches documents where the specified field exists. Note that the field's value should have been indexed.
Wildcard Query: This query supports wildcard patterns to match documents based on a pattern
Prefix Query: It matches documents that have fields containing terms with a specified prefix.
Nested Query: Used to query nested objects withing documents.


Match Query:

Elasticsearch uses analyzers to process and tokenize text before indexing. By default, the Match Query uses the analyzer associated with the field you're searching on. This can lead to better results, especially with languages that have stemming and other linguistic variations.

Here we are not just finding out text, we also consider how well it matches out our text (relevance).

Relevance score: Measures how well each document matches a query.
gives the results in sorted order, the doc with high relevance score us at the top.

by default the operation is 'or'


keyword type:

when the field type is keyword, then analyzer wont tokenize, lowercase. It stores the field as it is.

Example: Cricket

when you run a query match for the field bio with term as Cricket, the documents which have Cricket in bio will be returned, but the documents with cricket as bio wont be considered. since they differ in case.

when you try to do the same in bio which is of text type, will return all document that has Cricket/cricket etc

Disjunction Max Query:

It is useful for situations where you have multiple query clauses representing different aspects of a search, and you want to ensure that documents any of these clauses are returned.












